Let me start with the conclusion. In my personal opinion, “Sihai” is a completely terrible movie in every sense.
But if you say this movie has no highlights at all, that wouldn’t be quite right; at least the soundtrack is quite good.
There are many types of bad movies, and the ones that make you fall asleep soundly in the cinema are one kind; those that leave you filled with outrage after watching are another. “The Four Seas” is like the monkeys on Mount Emei to the audience—it can ignite your anger in countless ways.
Han Han truly has an extraordinary talent when it comes to insulting the audience.
The most painful aspect of this film is that it seems to be a creation out of a Kafkaesque novel—indescribable and full of flaws, just like the trench coat worn by the character Marco.
Even after watching it, you might wonder if there are any metaphors hidden by the director, but upon further reflection, you realize that it’s just a pile of shit.
Let me first briefly explain some plot elements that I find really difficult to understand.
The protagonist lives on a small island in the southern part of the country, relying on his grandmother for support.
Her grandmother had a wish to see snow, and then the plot arranged for an elderly man from the neighborhood to drive her there in a small van to the northeast to see the snow.
Are elderly people traveling from the south to the northeast in a van just to see the snow???
He and his dad are still very confident about this.
And then that old man’s story just ends there, with no further development.
How did the female protagonist’s brother obtain the business license to open a hotel on an abandoned ship?
Why are those petty gang members from the motorcycle club on the island able to easily block off a section of the mountain road??
Then the truck that was delivering steel rebar in the middle of the road stopped by the side of the road, and not even the truck driver could be found anywhere in the vicinity.
The sense of it being just a prop is too obvious, isn’t it?
How could a small-time thug with a poor credit record and suspected involvement in illegal activities become a police officer on a part-time basis?
Why don’t they call the police when facing usury? In the movie, the police even specifically ask if there are any difficulties.
An adult knows how to use a smartphone, but doesn’t know how to open a hotel room door with a card. Then they forcefully try to find the hotel owner, but can’t locate them, so they end up sleeping outside the room door for the night?
These utterly inexplicable plot elements are present throughout the entire film, and because they are so absurd, recalling them causes me pain.
Apart from the plot, what’s even worse is the main theme of the movie—or rather, the fact that the movie doesn’t have any real theme at all. It’s just a repulsive, stitched-together mess.
At the beginning of the movie, you might think he wants to make a comedy. After about 20 minutes, you might guess it could be an inspirational film. Halfway through, you start to think it might be a drama that aims to show the difficulties young people in a small town face. By the end, you’re completely confused about what you just watched, which leads to deep self-doubt. Why on New Year’s Day would you go to the cinema to watch something so… well, let’s just say, not very interesting?
For most people, the tropes of different types of movies are actually quite familiar. For example, if you want to make a movie about a motorcycle rider, it would usually follow an inspiring and comedic storyline, showing how a talented newcomer gradually achieves success step by step.
If you want to make a love movie, then just honestly tell the story of the complicated relationships between a young guy from the town who likes riding motorcycles and a waitress girl.
If you want to reflect reality, then at the very least your plot shouldn’t contain anything that contradicts the normal world.
(For example, the character played by Yoon Jung, whose new motorcycle just got burned down but who can still sing…) One shouldn’t come up with such crazy ideas that even Kennedy wouldn’t be able to handle.
As for the female protagonist, who clearly isn’t mentally disabled but behaves in some ways like a 5-year-old child, I really don’t know whether it’s due to her acting skills or the director’s requirements.
There’s another thing I really can’t understand: Why is Han Han, as a racing driver, so keen on including car crash scenes in his own movies?
Is such a movie being scheduled during the Spring Festival just to cause trouble for the audience?
