South African doctor: Although Omicron is highly contagious, most cases are mild.
Many doctors and medical experts in South Africa believe that the symptoms caused by the Omicron variant of the COVID-19 virus are milder than those of the Delta variant, although Omicron spreads more quickly.
According to the Associated Press, as the Omicron variant spreads in South Africa, a medical organization consisting of more than 5,000 doctors in the Gauteng province has reported that the symptoms exhibited by the COVID-19 patients they are treating are relatively mild, such as body aches and coughs, which are similar to those of the flu.
Dr. Unben Pillay, the director of the organization, said that he sees dozens of patients every day, but so far none of them have required hospitalization.
Pillai said, “They are able to control the disease at home, and most people recover within 10 to 14 days of isolation.”
He said that this includes elderly patients and those with underlying health issues, who are already more likely to develop severe symptoms from a coronavirus infection.
He said that, in comparison, during the previous wave of the Delta pandemic, the COVID-19 patients he treated “had difficulty breathing and low blood oxygen levels.”
Many people will need to be hospitalized within a few days.
Within two weeks of the first reports of the Omicron variant in Southern Africa, other doctors also shared similar experiences.
Although it will still take a few weeks to collect sufficient data, the doctor’s observations and preliminary evidence have provided some clues.
According to a summary by the South African National Institute for Communicable Diseases: Among the COVID-19 patients hospitalized in recent weeks, only 30% had severe cases, which is half the proportion of severe cases during the previous wave of the pandemic; the average length of hospital stay has decreased from 8 days to 2.8 days; and only 3% of the recent COVID-19 patients have died, compared to a mortality rate of 20% among the cases that emerged in the early stages of the outbreak in South Africa.
Willem Hanekom, the director of the African Institute for Health Research, cited data from the National Institute of Infectious Diseases and other reports, stating: “At present, almost all indications suggest that this is a milder form of the disease.”
He also said, “We are still in the early stages; we need to obtain data from later periods.”
Normally, hospitalizations and deaths occur at a later stage, yet we have only been in this wave of the pandemic for two weeks.”
Meanwhile, scientists around the world are observing the number of cases and hospitalization rates, while also testing the effectiveness of the current vaccines and treatment methods.
Although Delta remains the dominant strain of the COVID-19 virus worldwide, Omicron cases are emerging in dozens of countries, with South Africa at the center of the outbreak.
According to health officials, the number of new cases in the province of Gauteng increased by 400% in the first week of December. Tests have shown that the Omicron variant accounts for more than 90% of the cases.
