The International Olive Oil Association classifies olive oil into two main categories: Virgin Olive Oil and Lampante Olive Oil (also known as Refined Olive Oil), with a total of five different grades.
Extra virgin olive oil, also known as natural olive oil, is obtained by mechanically cold-pressing fresh olive fruits. The oil is then filtered to remove any impurities.
Depending on the acidity level, they can be divided into three categories:
Extra Virgin Olive Oil: This is the highest grade and highest quality of olive oil, and it is a completely natural product.
The taste is excellent, with a delicate and pleasant floral aroma, and the acidity does not exceed 1%.
Fine Virgin olive oil: It has a slightly higher acidity, but not exceeding 2%, and boasts a pure, aromatic flavor.
Ordinary Virgin Olive Oil: The taste and flavor are acceptable, with an acidity not exceeding 3.3%.
Refined olive oil refers to olive oil that has been obtained by refining extra virgin olive oil with an acidity level exceeding 3.3%, and is also known as "second-hand oil."
Refined olive oil can be divided into two grades:
Regular Olive Oil: A blend of refined olive oil and a certain proportion of extra-virgin olive oil, designed to balance the flavor and color. It has an acidity of less than 1.5% and appears as a clear, light golden yellow liquid.
Refined Olive-Pomace Oil: This is an olive oil that is obtained by extracting it from the oil residue using a dissolution method and then undergoing refinement processes.
If you have seen the classification systems, you should have already realized that the acidity of olive oil is a very important indicator.
You should know that olives are similar to the grapes used for making wine; olives from different regions and varieties will produce olive oil of varying quality.
The best areas for the growth of oil olives:
The Mediterranean coast possesses the most ideal soil conditions, as well as the right climate parameters such as temperature, sunlight, air humidity, and precipitation levels required for the growth of oil olives.
Apart from the Mediterranean coast, in other areas, it can only be planted sporadically in suitable habitats.
Main production area (Mediterranean):
Italy, Spain, Greece, Turkey, Portugal, Morocco, Syria, Israel, Tunisia, Algeria, Egypt, Pakistan, Lebanon, and so on. Countries with similar climates can also be found much further south in latitude, such as Argentina, Peru, and South Africa.
Months of harvesting oil olives:
From March to June each year, the olive trees bloom and set fruit. From July to October, the fruit begins to develop and ripen, changing color from green to red, then purple, and finally to black.
The fruit-picking season is from November to February of the following year (the freshness of olive oil is really important, you know!).
Nutritional components of olive oil:
Olive oil is rich in monounsaturated fatty acids, namely oleic acid, linoleic acid, and linolenic acid, as well as vitamins A, B, D, E, K, and antioxidants.
Olive oil is considered to be the most suitable fat for human nutrition among all the oils that have been discovered to date.
The Democratic Summit has concluded, and Biden stated that the flame of freedom will never go out.
The online “Summit for Democracy,” convened by U.S. President Joe Biden and attended by leaders from governments of 110 countries around the world, as well as representatives from civil society and the private sector, concluded on Friday (December 10).
In his closing remarks, Biden said that the flame of freedom burns in the hearts of everyone in the world, and authoritarian regimes can never extinguish it.
He also stated that there are plans to hold the second Global “Democracy Summit” next year.
Tang Fenghe, a representative of the Taiwan government and a member of the Administrative Council, as well as Luo Guancong, a Hong Kong civil rights activist currently in exile in the UK, also spoke at the summit on the second day.
Biden said, “We know how daunting the task ahead of us is.”
But we also know that we can meet the challenges head-on, because as I have said before, and as this summit has demonstrated, the democratic world is everywhere.
Autocratic regimes can never extinguish the tiny flame of freedom; it burns in the hearts of people all over the world.”
Biden also stated that defending democracy requires the joint efforts of the entire society.
He said, “As leaders of the government, it is our responsibility to listen to our citizens, strengthen the safeguards of democracy, promote reforms, and achieve transparent and accountable governance. This will help us better withstand the forces of tyranny and those who seek power at the expense of the public interest.”
The themes for the second day of the “Democracy Summit” were respectively: defending human rights, strengthening democracy and combating authoritarianism; as well as responding to digital authoritarianism and affirming the values of democracy.
This day coincides with “International Human Rights Day”.
United Nations Secretary-General António Guterres also stated in his opening speech of the day that the cause of democracy faces challenges worldwide, particularly those brought about by emerging digital technologies.
He said, “It is now time to reaffirm our common values and positions, as well as the resilience of democracy.”
This requires deepening social dialogue, addressing issues of inequality, fighting corruption, renewing the social contract, investing in quality education, and expanding opportunities for women and girls.
This also requires a firm condemnation of all forms of populism, nationalism, and extremism, including the use of all the tools provided by the technological revolution.
Hong Kong civil rights and democracy activist Luo Guancong delivered a speech at the summit through a pre-recorded video, reminding participants to continue to pay attention to the human rights situation in Hong Kong as well as that of China's ethnic minorities, such as the Uyghurs and Tibetans.
He said, “For a long time, the world has accepted China’s rise without establishing a mechanism to hold it accountable.”
This is why political figures and leaders from civil society must work together.
We must make use of everything we have at our disposal to ensure that the revival of democracy is our top priority.
Lo Kwan-chung also called on the free world to unite against the threat posed by the Chinese Communist Party.
He said, “Perhaps some of you are afraid of offending General Secretary Xi Jinping, perhaps some of you don’t want to lose the Chinese market, and perhaps some of you haven’t realized the threat that the Communist Party of China poses to our democratic values.”
And this is the reason why we failed.
This is also the reason why we must make changes.
Tang Feng, a member of the Executive Yuan of Taiwan, delivered a National Statement via video during a roundtable discussion on "Combating Digital Dictatorship and Affirming Democratic Values," emphasizing that Taiwan is at the forefront of the fight against authoritarianism and tyranny.
He also shared his experiences on how to combat the COVID-19 pandemic through transparency in information and the building of mutual trust.
He said, “As democracy in Taiwan is still in its early stages of development, we have always firmly stood at the forefront of the global fight against authoritarianism. Moreover, we play a leading role in promoting freedom, democracy, and human rights around the world.”
During the pandemic, authoritarian governments around the world have justified violations of human rights in the name of public health and the greater good, indicating a regression in global democracy.
However, in Taiwan, we are able to control the epidemic without having to impose lockdowns, and we can defeat fake information without having to remove it from circulation.
On the second day of the “Democracy Summit,” while the agenda was underway, the U.S. Treasury Department announced the imposition of sanctions on 15 individuals and 10 entities from countries such as China and North Korea, which were identified for serious violations of human rights. Additionally, investment restrictions were imposed on a Chinese company deemed to have used surveillance technology to assist in those human rights abuses.
