On the eve of Credit Suisse’s “Double Twelve” promotion, the company advocated for rational consumption among consumers – Economic Observation Network, a professional financial news website
This year, during the “Double Eleven” shopping festival, the total transaction amount for online payments across the country reached 1.77 trillion yuan, setting a new record compared to previous years.
The diverse range of promotional red envelopes offering discounts and bonuses, along with the eye-catching live-streaming sales events, have once again allowed consumers to feel that they are getting a great deal. On one hand, this surge in consumption highlights the growing purchasing power of the nation's citizens; on the other hand, it also forces us to take a more cautious look at the impact of consumerism on society and the contemporary mainstream consumer group.
On the eve of “Double Twelve,” Joy Credit Consumer Finance Co., Ltd. (hereinafter referred to as “Joy Credit”) issued a call for rational consumption, reminding users, especially young people, to develop good consumption awareness and habits, and to avoid blind and excessive spending.
According to the results of the “Consumer Financial Literacy Survey and Analysis Report” released by the People’s Bank of China this year, the national consumer financial literacy index has reached 66.81, an increase of 2.04 compared to 2019.
Overall, the residents of our country perform well in terms of financial consumption. However, there are significant differences in various aspects of financial behavior and skills, indicating a need for further improvement in basic financial knowledge.
The levels of financial literacy among the elderly and teenagers are relatively low, and these two groups will continue to be a focus of financial education efforts. According to the “China Youth Debt Report” published by Nielsen and the “2019-2020 China Youth Consumption Report” released by CCTV Finance, the younger generation possesses significant consumer potential. Credit consumption has become an important means of upgrading consumption patterns; 86.6% of young people use credit products, and nearly half of them have no accumulated debt. Although the overall trend among the youth is one of rational consumption, which contrasts with the label of “excessive
As a licensed consumer finance institution, Joyoung has always been committed to helping people build their happy lives with high-quality and considerate services. It promotes the establishment of healthy and correct consumption attitudes among consumers and actively responds to regulatory calls by taking practical actions to enhance the rational consumption awareness of consumers, especially the younger generation.
Over the past several years, Credit Suisse has continuously carried out comprehensive and diverse financial education initiatives targeting young people, including college students. By collaborating with top domestic institutions and organizing innovative practice competitions, the company has subtly guided the consumption needs of this demographic, helping them develop a rational approach to spending and plan their financial expenditures effectively, thereby contributing to the accumulation of personal wealth.
As Double Twelve approaches, Joy Credit reminds all consumers to develop a reasonable sense of consumption and a correct view of money. It urges them to resist impulsive and excessive spending, and to avoid misconceptions about consumer loans, in order to prevent negative impacts on their personal credit records and future financial well-being.
When making purchases, it is essential to plan in advance, spend within your means, and repay the loans on time.
If the payment is overdue, the overdue record will be included in the individual’s credit report, which may have negative consequences on future financial activities such as purchasing a car or a house.
At the same time, when enjoying financial products and services, it is important to choose legitimate institutions and channels, and to verify whether the relevant organizations have the necessary qualifications to operate.
In the future, Joyoung will, as always, rely on its mature and reliable consumer finance system as well as continuously updated financial products to provide consumers with services that better meet their needs and are more diverse. It will continue to help the public improve their financial knowledge, foster the concept of rational consumption and moderate borrowing, and become a trusted partner in consumer finance throughout their lives.
