Claimed to have the loudest exhaust sound among supercars in the New Mountain District!
The car that our team has brought for everyone this time is the dream of many men!
It is the flagship supercar from Lamborghini, the successor to the Murcielago – the Aventador LP700-4!
The price is nearly two million Malaysian ringgit, and the annual road tax is just over ten thousand Malaysian ringgit. It’s a four-wheel-drive vehicle – so why is it called the LP700?
With 700 horsepower, you can imagine how fast it would be.
Well, I don’t really know either. The data shows that the acceleration from 0 to 100 km/h only takes 2.9 seconds. That means by the time my Myvi reaches 30 km/h, the other vehicle might already be going at 100 km/h. Hmm.
The low-profile car body, the imposing scissor doors, the large air inlets surrounding the entire vehicle, and the 6.5-liter V12 engine clearly visible through the glass perfectly embody the Lamborghini style.
There’s not much need to say about the car model itself; just Google it if you want to know more. The editor has compiled some additional information that might not be available directly through Google searches!
It’s too much attention; wherever I go, everyone is looking at me, which makes me very uncomfortable! (Actually, it’s kind of exhilarating too.)
The cost of fuel for a 1-kilometer journey is around RM1 (the car owner doesn’t really care about it at all).
You should practice the posture for getting in and out of the vehicle; otherwise, it might be a bit awkward (because you might not be able to get out of the cabin and get stuck halfway).
The engine noise is so loud that you’ll go deaf as soon as you get out of the car. (But it’s still really exciting.)
The car is too large; it would be very cramped if parked in a regular parking space. I’m really worried about getting hit by the door of the car next to it when it gets opened!
It’s a bit lonely because there are no competitors on the road (that’s what the editor said; it has nothing to do with the car owners, haha).
Let there be no misunderstanding: the supercar in this video is not for sale. Sorry!
Friends who want to record videos of their beloved cars are welcome to contact us!
For more car information that you don’t know, check out The Car Guide / People’s Car Magazine.
