Negative nucleic acid test results within 48 hours, and the establishment of “buffer zones.” The Joint Prevention and Control Mechanism of the State Council has issued a document calling for enhanced epidemic prevention and control measures in port cities – Xinhua News Agency
Xinhua News Agency, Beijing, December 11 (Reporters Dong Ruifeng, Gu Tiancheng) The Joint Prevention and Control Mechanism of the State Council recently issued a notice on strengthening the prevention and control of the COVID-19 pandemic in port cities. It requires that individuals who leave land border port cities (except those connected to Hong Kong and Macau by ports) must provide a negative nucleic acid test result within 48 hours, and those traveling to such cities must undergo at least one nucleic acid test upon arrival.
According to the notification, the time frame for the above requirements is from the date when each province, autonomous region, and municipality determines the list of port cities and announces it, until March 15, 2022.
In addition, the notification also suggests that port cities with the appropriate conditions may consider establishing buffer zones for epidemic prevention and control within their jurisdictions.
A responsible official from the Disease Prevention and Control Bureau of the National Health Commission explained that for some port cities, cross-border trade is a major economic pillar, with frequent exchanges between residents on both sides of the border.
By implementing a differentiated management policy based on zoning, the approach has shifted from having just one line of defense against the spread of the outbreak to having two lines of defense. This change is expected to move the focus of prevention and control further forward, thereby reducing the risk of the outbreak spreading. The goal is to achieve the greatest effectiveness in epidemic prevention and control with the least social impact and at the lowest social cost.
Recently, several local cluster outbreaks have occurred in our country, all of which were imported from overseas epidemics through port cities.
The aforementioned notice indicates that these issues have been exposed, such as the lack of timely epidemic monitoring and early warning in some areas, the failure to implement closed-loop management for personnel in high-risk positions, the perfunctory nature of regular nucleic acid testing, inadequate disinfection at all stages of the cold chain, non-standard management of centralized isolation facilities, and the insufficiently scientific and precise response to epidemics.
The notification requires efforts to be made in nine areas, including improving the epidemic prevention and control mechanisms in port cities, enhancing the epidemic monitoring and early warning systems, and implementing border control measures. The aim is to quickly address the shortcomings and weaknesses in the prevention and control capabilities of these cities. Efforts must be relentless, scientific, and precise, in order to establish a robust defense against the introduction of infections from outside.
The notification emphasizes that cities with ports should conduct simultaneous research and planning for both epidemic prevention and control measures and the provision of public welfare services. They should make the hotlines for public welfare services readily accessible, regularly monitor potential issues related to the supply of essential living materials and prices, and promptly address and respond to the prominent concerns raised by the public.
According to the notice, the port cities referred to include the counties (cities, districts, banners) where the open land, water, and air ports are located, as well as the cities (prefectures, states, leagues) and municipalities directly under the Central Government where these ports are situated. The specific scope will be determined by each province (autonomous region, municipality directly under the Central Government) based on the needs of epidemic prevention and control, and will be announced in a timely manner.
