In the past two years, the United States’ blockade and encirclement of Huawei’s chips have not only plunged Huawei into unprecedented difficulties but also caused significant losses for “American-style” companies.
The United States is suppressing China’s chip industry by urging its own companies and those of its allied countries to also impose sanctions on China’s chip industry. As a direct result, the orders and profits of global chip suppliers have been affected, leading to reduced research and development investment by chip manufacturers and decreased production capacity. This has in turn caused disruptions in the global chip supply chain.
Today, the "chip shortage" has affected various industries around the world, such as car manufacturers stopping production and mobile phone prices rising. Almost all industries that use chips have been severely impacted by this issue.
In order to gain control over the autonomy of “chips,” technology giants from an increasing number of countries are starting to pursue a path of “de-romanticization” (i.e., removing the glamor or idealized image associated with these technologies).
In order to firmly maintain control over the global semiconductor industry and curb the development of China’s semiconductor sector, the United States has been quite active recently. They have hosted a “Chip Summit,” invited giants from 64 countries to form a semiconductor alliance, and provided funding to support domestic American tech companies. For instance, Intel, a leading American technology company, has invested $20 billion to build two new wafer processing plants in Arizona, with the aim of regaining its dominant position in the chip industry. They have also opened up their chip manufacturing services to external partners.
When most people thought that Intel’s move would have a certain impact on TSMC and could very likely take away TSMC’s business,
I am so certain of this because Intel, as a established technology giant in the United States, has been deeply involved in the semiconductor industry for decades. With its large pool of talent and technical reserves, it is definitely capable of rising rapidly in a short period of time and surpassing TSMC.
However, TSMC founder Terry Gou dismissed Intel’s decision as insignificant.
At the “2021 Masters Think Tank Forum” held in April this year, Terry Gou made a surprising statement. Regarding Intel’s decision to invest in building a wafer factory, he spoke without any hesitation: “It’s quite ironic that Intel is establishing a chip foundry.”
The reason why Zhang Zhongmou holds such disdain for Intel's entry into the wafer manufacturing industry is that he still harbors resentment over a conflict between TSMC and Intel that occurred over 30 years ago.
In the 1960s and 1970s, Intel was the crown jewel of American manufacturing, occupying a dominant position at the global forefront and ruling the semiconductor industry.
By the 1980s, the high-end semiconductor chips in the world were still in the hands of a few powerful companies.
At that time, the semiconductor industry was characterized by the IDM (Integrated Device Manufacturing) model, where the entire process from chip design, manufacturing to packaging and testing was carried out by a single company. Intel was the representative of that era.
However, this model places a heavy burden on some small businesses, and many semiconductor entrepreneurs are deterred by the enormous costs associated with building production lines.
Inspired by market demand, the chip industry began to exhibit a phenomenon of division of labor and cooperation in the 1980s. In 1984, Zhang Zhongmou heard about companies that specialized in chip design and realized that since there were companies dedicated to this task, it would be possible to establish a factory focused solely on wafer manufacturing.
Not long after, TSMC’s vision came to fruition, and the company was born.
TSMC has focused its main business on the single process of “wafer fabrication.” It does not engage in design activities but only provides contract manufacturing services for wafer production.
At that time, TSMC, which had just been established, was nothing but a tiny player in the face of the giant Intel.
In order to obtain capital support, Zhang Zhongmou approached Intel for investment. However, when Intel learned that TSMC was only involved in the manufacturing aspect of the chip industry, they seemed quite arrogant and looked down on TSMC, ultimately deciding to reject the investment proposal.
Jack Zhang also believes that Intel looked down on wafer manufacturing services at that time.
It’s surprising that the giants who used to look down on wafer manufacturing services are now also starting to engage in wafer foundry operations.
So, Zhang Zhongmou found it ironic that Intel entered the wafer foundry business.
Today, TSMC's market value has surpassed that of Intel.
Faced with TSMC's strong offensive, Intel naturally cannot afford to stand still and become complacent.
Today, TSMC is already working on 3nm chips, while Intel is still stuck at the 14nm technology from 7 years ago.
Trying to catch up or surpass someone isn’t actually that easy.
