Starry Sky Appointment | The Geminid Meteor Shower will reach its peak on the 14th - Xinhua News Agency
Xinhua News Agency, Tianjin, December 12 (Reporter Zhou Runjian) According to astronomy experts, the Geminid meteor shower, one of the three major meteor showers in the Northern Hemisphere and also the last large-scale meteor shower of the year, will reach its peak on December 14. Friends who enjoy watching meteor showers can observe it in the latter half of the night on that day.
The Geminid meteor shower, photographed by An Jiu, an astronomy enthusiast from Beijing, on December 13, 2018, in Qinghai.
The parent bodies of most meteor showers are periodic comets, but the parent body of the Geminid meteor shower is asteroid 3200 Phaethon, which is an Apollo-type asteroid.
The Geminid meteor shower is also the second known meteor shower that is not originated from a comet.
Xiu Lipeng, a member of the Tianjin Astronomical Society and an expert in popularizing astronomy, explained that, just like the blockbuster New Year’s movies, the Geminid meteor shower usually occurs at the end of the year, with its “screening period” lasting from December 4th to December 17th.
This meteor shower is known for its high and steady rate of meteor appearances. Along with the Quadrantid meteor shower and the Perseid meteor shower, it is considered one of the three major meteor showers in the Northern Hemisphere.
A notable feature of the Geminid meteor shower is the relatively slow speed of the meteoroids, as well as their rich range of colors and the presence of many fireballs. This makes it an excellent opportunity for both amateur observers and beginners in astrophotography to capture stunning images.
The Geminid meteor shower, photographed by Yang Jing, an astronomy enthusiast from Tianjin, on December 13, 2020, in Jizhou, Tianjin.
Astronomical forecasts indicate that this year’s Geminid meteor shower will reach its peak around 15:00 on December 14th, with a ZHR (Zenith Hourly Rate) of 150 – meaning the number of meteors visible per hour under ideal observation conditions, when the radiant point is directly above the observer’s head.
Gemini Meteor Shower Recommendation Index Chart.
“Last year, the Geminid meteor shower, known for its beautiful display of falling stars, left a deep impression on everyone. However, this year’s Geminid shower will be affected by moonlight, which may reduce the intensity of the show a bit.”
The 14th falls on the 11th day of the 11th lunar month, which is a waxing gibbous moon phase. The bright moonlight can interfere with observations. Fortunately, the moon will set in the latter half of the night, and at that time, the radiant point of the Geminid meteor shower will also be higher in the sky.
Friends who enjoy meteor showers can observe them in the hours after the moon sets in the latter half of the night, but be sure to keep warm to avoid catching a cold.
How can one observe as many meteors as possible?
“It is not recommended to conduct observations in urban areas. One can choose a location in the suburbs or countryside that is at a high altitude, has minimal light pollution, and offers a clear view in the northeast direction. Then, one should wait patiently for the moon to set before conducting the observation visually.”
It should be noted that the Geminid meteor shower has a high rate of meteors coming from various directions, so there's no need to constantly watch the radiant point of the shower during observation.
Friends who enjoy photography and want to capture stunning ‘meteor shower’ photos should opt for a wide-angle lens with a large aperture. When shooting, use a high ISO setting and the maximum aperture of the lens.
Considering stability and durability, a tripod, spare batteries, and a remote control for the shutter are also essential.
Xiu Lipeng reminded them.
What are the differences in market positioning between laser TVs and traditional TVs?
From my understanding, the traditional TV mentioned by the questioner should refer to a liquid crystal television (LCD TV). The main differences in market positioning between laser TVs and LCD TVs are as follows:
Firstly, laser TVs are more focused on the large-screen market.
Compared to the market positioning of LCD TVs, which are widely available, laser TVs seem to focus more on the large-screen market. In other words, laser TVs are essentially products designed for large screens.
Currently, the sizes of mainstream LCD TVs range from 55 to 65 inches, while laser TVs generally have a size of 75 inches or more, with the largest models exceeding 100 inches, fully meeting users' demand for large-screen color TVs.
In recent years, the shipment volume and sales percentage of laser TVs have been continuously increasing globally. They account for more than 60% of the total TV sales in the 80-inch and larger size category.
According to the predictions of CICAC, in 2020, the sales volume of laser TVs is expected to grow by more than 140%, continuing to maintain a high growth rate.
The reason for such excellent results in the large-screen market is mainly due to the outstanding performance of laser TVs in terms of eye protection.
Based on the principle of diffuse reflection in laser TVs, the light emitted by the laser source does not directly enter the eye. Compared to the backlight of LCD TVs, this imaging process is more similar to how objects are perceived under natural conditions, resulting in less strain on the eyes.
Experts from the CCSTC SICE Laboratory and the Ophthalmology Department of Peking Union Medical College Hospital conducted a rigorous comparative study involving people watching both laser TVs and LCD TVs under the same conditions, resulting in 144 sets of test data.
The data confirms that laser TVs indeed have strong eye-protecting properties and can even have a positive effect in certain aspects.
In an era where vision health is receiving increasing attention, laser TVs have not only attracted more and more users due to their benefits for eye protection but have also opened up a new breakthrough in the color TV market.
Secondly, laser TVs are more targeted at the high-end market.
Contrary to the continuous decline in the prices of LCD TVs, the prices of laser TVs currently available on the market are mostly over 10,000 yuan. As the size and light source of these TVs improve, their prices are gradually increasing.
Why are laser TVs so expensive?
There must be some logic to it.
With the continuous advancement of light sources and technological levels, laser TVs possess many advantages that liquid crystal TVs and projectors are unable to achieve.
Thanks to their ultra-short-throw projection technology, laser TVs require a much shorter projection distance compared to traditional projectors. This allows for a 100-inch large-screen experience at a close range, requiring minimal space. Additionally, the main unit of the laser TV is compact and takes up very little room.
In terms of brightness, high-brand laser TVs can achieve luminosities of over 2000 lumens.
Furthermore, with a lower heat generation, the wear and tear on the equipment is reduced, resulting in a longer lifespan for the television.
In addition to this, many high-end laser TV models are equipped with a true 4K ultra-high definition display, artificial intelligence systems, bionic screens, and numerous other cutting-edge technologies, providing users with an even more stunning visual and auditory experience.
It’s not so much a case of “pseudo-demand” as rather the result of a more detailed segmentation of market needs. In terms of image quality and cost-effectiveness, laser TVs are not the right choice for audio-visual enthusiasts. If you want to combine a large screen with a suitable viewing environment but face certain limitations, you could still give it a try. Everything has its pros and cons; you should make your own judgment after weighing all the factors. The main thing to avoid is trusting only one side of the story.
In simple terms, ultra-wide-angle, short-throw projectors (such as laser TVs) have to use expensive ultra-wide-angle lenses and mirrors in order to get the image close to the screen. This does not conform to the principles of optimal optical design.
In order to block some of the ambient light, using a microstructured Fresnel screen comes at a high cost; the price of an 80-inch screen is roughly equivalent to that of a 65-inch LCD screen.
One more thing: I really dislike how projector manufacturers use the argument that diffused light is good for the eyes as a selling point. Seriously, the light from the screen that reaches the eyes is actually direct light. Even if the light is diffused and then bounces off the ceiling, the eyes can’t see it. Moreover, LCD TVs also emit diffused (but still direct) light; doesn’t turning on the TV also illuminate the ceiling?
Moreover, if the projection screen does not exhibit diffuse reflection, it simply cannot form an image.
It’s precisely the hot spot (light spot) effect of high-gain screens that is often overlooked. A large amount of light reflected at a certain angle into the eyes can be truly uncomfortable.
